## Tailwind Usage with Brand Colors

Use `var()` inside Tailwind's square-bracket notation for design token colors:

```jsx
// ✅ Backgrounds
<section className="bg-[#001439]">                        // navy bg
<div className="bg-[#002060]">                            // card bg
<div className="bg-[rgba(159,204,255,0.15)]">             // sky tint bg

// ✅ Text
<h2 className="text-[#9FCCFF]">                           // sky — headers
<p className="text-white">                                // white — body
<span className="text-[#2A8CD5]">                         // blue — labels/links

// ✅ Borders
<div className="border border-[#2A8CD5]">                 // blue border
<div className="border border-[rgba(42,140,213,0.25)]">   // subtle border

// ✅ Buttons
<button className="bg-[#2A8CD5] hover:bg-[#1e6fab] text-white">
<button className="border border-[#2A8CD5] text-[#9FCCFF] hover:bg-[rgba(42,140,213,0.1)]">
```

---

```jsx
// ✅ CORRECT — conditional classes with cn()
import { cn } from '@/lib/utils/cn'

<button
  className={cn(
    'px-4 py-2 rounded-lg font-medium transition-colors',
    variant === 'primary' && 'bg-blue-700 text-white hover:bg-blue-600',
    variant === 'outline' && 'border border-sky-400 text-sky-400 hover:bg-sky-400/10',
    disabled && 'opacity-50 cursor-not-allowed',
    className   // always accept className prop for overrides
  )}
>

// ❌ WRONG — manual string concatenation
<button className={`px-4 py-2 ${variant === 'primary' ? 'bg-blue-700' : 'border'}`}>
```

